            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.4.30" />

                                                                                                                        <fw type="curatorial">30</fw>

                                                <fw type="letterhead">
                                                        Fairholt,
                                                        <lb/>
                                                    Burlington, Vermont.
                                                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                                                                                    <dateline>October 22, 1917</dateline>


                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It was very nice of yu<sic>you</sic> to write me on the 15th. When I see that that was a week ago, it strikes me as being pretty far between here and Bancroft, Nebraska.</p>
    
                <p>I don't know enuf<sic>enough</sic> about the educational side of my business to have an opinion as to the demand for such a book in schools, but if yu<sic>you</sic> will kindly have the <hi rend="caps">MS</hi>. sent to the office, I will take pleasure in having it thoroughly considered. The man who must finally pass on it is in California, but I suppose will be back in about ten days. Meanwhile probably it will have some preliminary examination.</p>
    
                <p>I have some superficial idea of your career since we saw each other, and have felt much interest in it. I have been wondering why I haven't been mixt<sic>mixed</sic> in more, and I have been cudgeling my brains to see if anything of yours  had come to us without being undertaken; but my brains don't yield me any information. I should be glad to hear from yu<sic>you</sic> about anything whatever; and if it's about a new book, shall consider it most earnestly.</p>
    
                <p>Do yu<sic>you</sic> ever see <title>The Unpopular Review</title> out your way &#8212; of which I am the unpopular editor?</p>
    
                <p>Yu<sic>You</sic> say it is a privilege to write a book"<hi rend="underline"><title>On the Civic Relations</title></hi> and then one <hi rend="underline"><title>On the Cosmic Relations</title></hi>." That depends on the book! The one <hi rend="underline"><title>On the Civic Relations</title></hi> was the deadest failure that I can recall. The other one has turned out satisfactorily.</p>

                <p>Do yu<sic>you</sic> remember my telling yu<sic>you</sic> in New York that yu<sic>you</sic> reminded me strongly of one of the dearest friends and most promising men I ever knew, who was cut off at about the age yu<sic>you</sic> were then? Your letter has been a double satisfaction to me, because it brought him up so vividly.</p>

                <p>With all good wishes,</p>
                <closer>
                                                 <salute>Faithfully yours</salute>
                    
                                                    <signed>H Holt</signed>

                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Esq.</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Bancroft, Nebr.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
